-- ============================================================
-- SOFWAVE SUPERB
-- Product ID: 78973d13-fa36-41dd-8625-4b851ff143ed
-- Category: Skin Tightening (4eb4c667-16af-44ba-94c6-e85edffef558)
-- Technology: Synchronous Ultrasound Parallel Beam (SUPERB), 7 transducer array, 1.5mm mid-dermis
-- FDA-cleared: facial lines and wrinkles (non-ablative)
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890',
  '78973d13-fa36-41dd-8625-4b851ff143ed',
  '4eb4c667-16af-44ba-94c6-e85edffef558',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'Sofwave SUPERB — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nSofwave SUPERB (Synchronous Ultrasound Parallel Beam) is a non-ablative, non-invasive ultrasound skin tightening device manufactured by Sofwave Medical. It is FDA-cleared for the treatment of facial lines and wrinkles, including improvement of submental (under-chin) and neck laxity. The SUPERB technology uses 7 parallel ultrasound transducer elements delivering focused ultrasound energy at a precise 1.5 mm depth within the mid-dermis, where collagen synthesis is most therapeutically effective. [Sofwave 510k K201789]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nSofwave SUPERB delivers multi-beam synchronous ultrasound at 3 MHz frequency. The seven parallel beams create cylindrical thermal coagulation zones (TCZs) within the mid-dermis at 1.5 mm depth. The integrated Sofcool simultaneous cooling of the epidermis protects the skin surface during energy delivery — a key design distinction that allows significant dermal heating without surface thermal injury. Dermal collagen responds to the focal thermal injury with a wound-healing cascade: collagen denaturation followed by type I collagen synthesis and dermal remodeling over 8–12 weeks. [Sofwave 510k; peer-reviewed: Alam M. Dermatol Surg 2021]\n\nKey difference from MFU-V (Ultherapy): Sofwave targets mid-dermis at 1.5 mm, not SMAS level. It is a pure skin quality/tightening treatment without the deep structural lifting of Ultherapy. This makes it appropriate for mild-moderate laxity and maintenance; very lax patients may need Ultherapy for SMAS-level lifting.\n\n## FDA-Cleared Indications\n\n- Improvement of **facial lines and wrinkles** in patients ≥22 years [FDA 510k K201789]\n- Improvement of submental area appearance and neck laxity [510k clearance expansion]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Ideal candidates:** Adults with mild-to-moderate facial laxity, fine-to-medium facial lines, early jawline softening. Excellent for patients who want meaningful improvement without injectables or surgery. Also suitable as a maintenance treatment for patients who have achieved results with deeper devices.\n\n**Excellent Fitzpatrick profile:** Sofwave has no direct skin contact energy delivery (cooled surface, ultrasound only) — no PIH risk from chromophore-based surface energy. Safe across all Fitzpatrick skin types. [peer-reviewed; 510k]\n\n**Poor candidacy / contraindications (Safety Floor):**\n- Active skin infection, open wounds, or severe active acne at treatment site\n- Metal implants, pacemakers, or implanted electronic devices in treatment area\n- Pregnancy\n- Very severe laxity requiring SMAS-level correction (Ultherapy or surgical facelift more appropriate)\n[Sofwave IFU]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Common:** Transient erythema and edema immediately post-treatment, resolving within hours to 48 hours. Mild tenderness at treatment sites. Very low adverse event profile in published literature.\n\n**Uncommon:** Transient pain during treatment (addressed with topical/oral analgesics); linear marks or bands from transducer tracks (rare, related to technique).\n\n**Rare/serious:** Burns from prolonged contact or device malfunction; nerve sensitivity (ultrasound in temporal, zygomatic area — stay within treatment depth parameters). [Sofwave IFU]\n\n**PIH risk:** Minimal to none — Sofcool surface protection and no chromophore targeting means PIH is not a clinical concern for Sofwave across skin types. [field practice; peer-reviewed]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes\n\nA prospective study (Alam M. et al., Dermatologic Surgery 2021) demonstrated statistically significant improvement in jawline, cheek, and neck laxity at 12 weeks post single treatment. Single-session treatment design is a notable positioning differentiator — most patients achieve meaningful improvement with one treatment (maintenance or touch-up at 12–18 months). [peer-reviewed: Alam M. Dermatol Surg 2021]',
  '36129552-10fb-4de1-88e0-24a034a8c972',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'b2c3d4e5-f6a7-8901-bcde-f12345678901',
  '78973d13-fa36-41dd-8625-4b851ff143ed',
  '4eb4c667-16af-44ba-94c6-e85edffef558',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'Sofwave SUPERB — Technique Guide',
  E'## Treatment Setup\n\n- Standard topical anesthetic (EMLA or compounded) 30–45 minutes pre-treatment; optional oral analgesic\n- Sofwave ultrasound gel applied to treatment area — appropriate coupling is essential for safe energy delivery and patient comfort\n- Facial grid marking optional to ensure complete coverage without over-treating zones\n\n## Treatment Delivery\n\nSofwave is a single-pass treatment. The 7-transducer array is moved in overlapping rows across the treatment area. The device provides real-time auditory feedback confirming energy delivery. Speed of movement affects energy density — slower movement per manufacturer protocol. Treat full face, including periorbital (with eye shields), cheeks, jawline, and neck as indicated.\n\n**Sofcool integration:** The simultaneous contact cooling is intrinsic to the device — it runs automatically during energy delivery. No separate cooling device needed. This distinguishes Sofwave from some ultrasound systems where surface protection is manually managed.\n\n**Gateway posture:** For exact energy level settings, pass counts, and speed parameters, refer to the Sofwave clinical training and IFU documentation [Sofwave IFU →].\n\n## Combination Sequencing\n\n- Sofwave + neurotoxin: same-session acceptable; BoNT addresses dynamic lines, Sofwave addresses dermal quality and mild laxity — complementary mechanisms\n- Sofwave + filler: energy device first if same-visit; wait 2–4 weeks post-Sofwave before filler in same zones if staged\n- Sofwave + Ultherapy: if patient needs both mid-dermis tightening and SMAS lifting, can be staged (Ultherapy for deep lifting, Sofwave for mid-dermis quality maintenance). Sources differ on same-session vs. staged.\n\n## Post-Treatment Protocol\n\n- No specific downtime; patients can return to normal activities immediately\n- SPF 30+ recommended for 2 weeks post-treatment\n- No restrictions on retinoids, exfoliants, or topicals post-treatment (no open wound)\n- Reassess at 12 weeks for touchup or maintenance planning',
  '128e4ca9-5016-4709-ba8a-fca44988d0fe',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-012345678902',
  '78973d13-fa36-41dd-8625-4b851ff143ed',
  '4eb4c667-16af-44ba-94c6-e85edffef558',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'Sofwave SUPERB — Patient Education',
  E'## What Sofwave Does\n\nSofwave SUPERB is a non-invasive skin tightening treatment that uses focused ultrasound to rebuild collagen inside your skin — without breaking the surface. It''s one of the most comfortable and zero-downtime options for addressing skin laxity, fine lines, and early jowling.\n\nThe technology works by delivering a precise beam of ultrasound energy to the exact depth in your skin where collagen is most responsive — 1.5 mm, right in the mid-dermis. A built-in cooling system protects the surface of your skin while the energy creates a controlled heating response in the collagen layer below. Your skin responds by rebuilding fresh collagen over the next 8–12 weeks.\n\n## What It Addresses\n\n- Mild to moderate facial laxity and sagging\n- Fine lines and medium depth wrinkles\n- Jawline softening and early jowling\n- Neck and under-chin laxity\n\n## Why Sofwave, Specifically\n\nSofwave is among the few skin tightening devices that works on all skin tones without pigmentation risk — because it doesn''t use light or heat at the surface. The simultaneous cooling protects the skin during treatment, which also means minimal downtime and remarkable comfort compared to treatments that intentionally injure the surface.\n\nMost patients complete the treatment in a single session. That''s not typical for skin tightening devices — Sofwave is designed as a one-treatment-per-year investment in skin quality.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**During the treatment:** Numbing cream applied beforehand makes the treatment comfortable. You will feel warmth during the session. Most treatments are completed in 45–60 minutes.\n\n**Afterward:** You can go directly back to your normal activities — there is no visible recovery. Mild redness for a few hours, then nothing.\n\n**Results:** Collagen rebuilds over 8–12 weeks; the full result is typically appreciated at 3 months. Maintenance treatment recommended every 12–18 months.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nSofwave addresses skin quality and mild laxity; it does not address volume or deep structural laxity. A complete plan may combine:\n- Sofwave for dermal tightening and line improvement\n- Neurotoxin (Botox) for dynamic movement-related lines\n- Dermal filler for volume restoration\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nSofwave is the skin tightening option for patients who want improvement without injection anxiety, without downtime, and without the recovery of more aggressive devices. If your concern is quality and mild-to-moderate laxity and you value convenience, this is the right tool. The tradeoff for that comfort is that very significant laxity requires a deeper intervention — which is a conversation worth having at your consultation.',
  '28bf58bf-f3d3-4eee-8f99-8e65ab1f4131',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'd4e5f6a7-b8c9-0123-defa-123456789003',
  '78973d13-fa36-41dd-8625-4b851ff143ed',
  '4eb4c667-16af-44ba-94c6-e85edffef558',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'Sofwave SUPERB — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"How is this different from Ultherapy?"**\nBoth use ultrasound, but they work at different depths. Sofwave targets the mid-dermis (1.5 mm) for skin quality and mild laxity. Ultherapy targets deeper layers including the SMAS (muscle-fascia layer), which enables more significant structural lifting. If your concern is mild-moderate tightening and skin quality, Sofwave is the right choice. If you need significant lifting of the brow, neck, or lower face, Ultherapy''s deeper reach may be more appropriate. Your provider can help you determine which is right for your anatomy.\n\n**"Is there downtime?"**\nEssentially none. You may have mild redness for a few hours, but most patients return directly to their day after treatment.\n\n**"Will it hurt?"**\nWith numbing cream, the treatment is comfortable for most patients — significantly more comfortable than devices that work at the surface with more aggressive energy. You will feel warmth during the treatment.\n\n**"Do I need to do it more than once?"**\nMost patients achieve meaningful results from a single treatment. Maintenance annually or every 18 months preserves the result as your skin naturally continues to age.\n\n**"Is it safe for my skin tone?"**\nYes — Sofwave does not use light or heat at the skin surface, so there is no risk of pigmentation changes. It is safe for all skin tones including darker complexions.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"I want to see results faster."**\nThe 8–12 week timeline for Sofwave''s result reflects the biology of collagen synthesis — the treatment works with your body''s own repair process, not against it. This is also why the result is natural-looking. Faster options exist (surface peels, lasers) but they do not address skin laxity in the same way.\n\n**"Is it really worth it if I can''t see it right away?"**\nThe result at 3 months is durable for 12–18 months in most patients. When you divide the treatment cost over the duration of result, Sofwave compares favorably to monthly maintenance treatments that require ongoing repeat visits.',
  '28bf58bf-f3d3-4eee-8f99-8e65ab1f4131',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'e5f6a7b8-c9d0-1234-efab-234567890004',
  '78973d13-fa36-41dd-8625-4b851ff143ed',
  '4eb4c667-16af-44ba-94c6-e85edffef558',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'Sofwave SUPERB — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\n**1.5 mm mid-dermis targeting with Sofcool:** The precise mid-dermis focus at 1.5mm is the defining technical specification. The integrated simultaneous epidermal cooling (Sofcool) enables aggressive mid-dermal heating without surface thermal risk — a combination that competing devices either don''t offer or require add-on cooling devices to accomplish.\n\n**Single-treatment design:** Clinical data support meaningful improvement from a single session — this differs from most energy device protocols requiring 3-session series. The single-treatment model is a practice-economics and patient-experience differentiator.\n\n**Fitzpatrick-universal:** Zero surface energy means zero chromophore-dependent PIH risk. Sofwave can treat the full Fitzpatrick range without protocol modification.\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\n3 MHz ultrasound, 7 parallel transducer elements, simultaneous delivery (synchronous). Focal depth 1.5 mm. Cylindrical TCZ diameter approximately 2 mm. Sofcool: integrated Peltier-element surface contact cooling to ~25°C during treatment. Collagen response pathway: thermal denaturation of type I and III collagen in TCZs → fibroblast recruitment → neocollagenesis over 8–12 weeks. Elastin co-synthesis described in some studies. [Sofwave 510k; Alam M. Dermatol Surg 2021]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\nAlam et al. (Dermatologic Surgery 2021): prospective study, statistically significant improvement in lower facial and neck laxity at 12 weeks post single treatment. Physician-assessed improvement rates in the 75–85% range. Safety across Fitzpatrick types reported. Evidence level: prospective study (Level II).\n\nAdditional published series in JCAD and Dermatology and Therapy confirm safety profile. Literature base is growing but smaller than established ultrasound platforms (Ultherapy).\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Feature | Sofwave SUPERB | Ultherapy PRIME | Thermage |\n|---------|---------------|-----------------|----------|\n| Depth | 1.5 mm (mid-dermis) | 1.5–4.5 mm (SMAS) | 2–6 mm (monopolar RF) |\n| Structural lift | Mild | Significant | Moderate |\n| Sessions needed | 1 | 1 | 1 |\n| PIH risk | None | None | None |\n| Comfort | High | Moderate | Moderate |\n| Key indication | Skin quality + mild laxity | Structural lifting | Skin tightening |',
  '129912ff-eee7-4ac9-bac2-4a3e4ac16036',
  'draft', 1
);

-- ============================================================
-- ULTHERAPY PRIME — Merz Aesthetics
-- Product ID: da25d447-c316-40b2-802e-e190c0bdbd9f
-- Category: Ultrasound Lifting (1c9acf3e-8753-4bd3-af98-9372c994eec3)
-- Technology: Micro-Focused Ultrasound with Visualization (MFU-V), SMAS-level
-- FDA-cleared: brow lift (unique clearance), neck/chin/chest lines/wrinkles
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'f6a7b8c9-d0e1-2345-fabc-345678900105',
  'da25d447-c316-40b2-802e-e190c0bdbd9f',
  '1c9acf3e-8753-4bd3-af98-9372c994eec3',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'Ultherapy PRIME — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nUltherapy PRIME is a non-invasive micro-focused ultrasound with visualization (MFU-V) device manufactured by Merz Aesthetics. It is the only non-invasive device with FDA clearance for a **non-invasive brow lift** — a unique positioning in the non-surgical facial rejuvenation category. Ultherapy delivers focused ultrasound to three precise tissue depths: 1.5 mm (upper dermis), 3 mm (deep dermis), and 4.5 mm (SMAS/platysma), using different transducer frequencies. The visualization feature (ultrasound imaging) allows the provider to see tissue layers in real time during treatment. [Ultherapy 510k K101445; FDA 510k clearances]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nUltherapy creates microscopic thermal coagulation points (TCPs) at precisely defined depths using focused ultrasound. At 4.5 mm depth, energy reaches the superficial muscular aponeurotic system (SMAS) and platysma — the fascial layer that surgeons lift during a facelift. Thermal injury to this layer triggers the same fibroblast-mediated repair response as surgical manipulation, producing collagen neosynthesis and tissue contracture. The lifting effect comes from both immediate TCP contraction and subsequent collagen remodeling over 2–3 months. [peer-reviewed: Kenkel JM. Aesthet Surg J 2014; Alam M. Dermatol Surg 2010]\n\nVisualization: the built-in ultrasound imaging system lets providers confirm transducer coupling and visualize tissue layers in real time — reducing the risk of suboptimal energy delivery.\n\n## FDA-Cleared Indications\n\n- **Non-invasive eyebrow lifting** (brow ptosis improvement) [510k — the ONLY non-invasive device with this clearance]\n- Improvement of lines and wrinkles on the **neck** and **under the chin** [510k]\n- Improvement of lines and wrinkles on the **chest** (décolletage) [510k]\n\n**Off-label field uses (gateway posture):** Full lower-face and mid-face lifting; jowl improvement; nasolabial fold softening via SMAS-level lifting. These are not enumerated in FDA clearances but are field-standard applications with substantial clinical evidence. [field practice; peer-reviewed]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Ideal candidates:** Adults with mild-to-moderate brow ptosis, early jowling, submental laxity, neck laxity, or décolletage wrinkling. Best results in patients with good skin quality (not severe laxity requiring surgical correction) and adequate subcutaneous tissue (very thin patients may have insufficient tissue mass for effective lifting response). [peer-reviewed: Kenkel JM. Aesthet Surg J 2014]\n\n**Fitzpatrick safety:** MFU-V has no surface energy — no PIH risk across skin types. Universal Fitzpatrick tolerance. [peer-reviewed; 510k]\n\n**Poor candidacy / contraindications (Safety Floor — FDA IFU, rank 1):**\n- Metal implants, pacemakers, defibrillators in treatment zone\n- Active skin infections, open wounds, cystic acne at treatment site\n- Pregnancy\n- Severe skin laxity more appropriate for surgical intervention\n- Dermal fillers recently placed in treatment zone (wait 4 weeks minimum; some protocols suggest 2 weeks with caution)\n[Ultherapy IFU; consensus]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Common (expected):** Temporary erythema and edema post-treatment, resolving within hours to days. Procedural pain/discomfort — Ultherapy is more intense than surface devices due to SMAS-level energy; adequate pre-medication (topical + NSAIDs + optional oral analgesic) is standard.\n\n**Uncommon:** Tenderness persisting >2 weeks; transient numbness or paresthesia (typically resolves within weeks from nerve proximity to energy delivery).\n\n**Rare/serious:** Motor nerve injury (marginal mandibular branch area — avoid direct energy delivery over known nerve trunk paths). Fat atrophy if energy delivered to superficial fat compartments with excessive settings (uncommon with standard protocols). [peer-reviewed; IFU]\n\n**Procedural pain management:** Ultherapy is one of the more uncomfortable energy treatments. Setting appropriate expectations and providing adequate pre-medication is essential for treatment completion and patient satisfaction. Some providers use local nerve blocks for high-energy protocols. [field practice]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes\n\nBrow lift: FDA clinical trial data. Statistically significant brow elevation at 90 days in 73.1% of subjects. [FDA 510k data]\nNeck/lower face: Multiple prospective studies showing statistically significant improvement in physician-assessed laxity and patient satisfaction at 90 days. [peer-reviewed: Alam M. Dermatol Surg 2010; Kenkel JM. Aesthet Surg J 2014]\nResult duration: 12–18 months typical with a single treatment; retreatment sustains results. Evidence level: prospective (Level II), supported by large real-world use base.',
  '76f2cc7d-1216-4b7b-ae49-90addfa26c9b',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'a7b8c9d0-e1f2-3456-abcd-456789001206',
  'da25d447-c316-40b2-802e-e190c0bdbd9f',
  '1c9acf3e-8753-4bd3-af98-9372c994eec3',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'Ultherapy PRIME — Technique Guide',
  E'## Transducer Selection\n\nUltherapy uses multiple transducer frequencies and focal depths. The PRIME system typically includes:\n- **DS 4-4.5 (DeepSEE):** 4 MHz, 4.5 mm depth — SMAS/platysma level for structural lifting\n- **DS 7-3.0:** 7 MHz, 3.0 mm depth — deep reticular dermis\n- **DS 10-1.5:** 10 MHz, 1.5 mm depth — upper dermis/dermal-subdermal junction\n\nProtocol typically combines 4.5 mm + 3.0 mm transducers for full-face/neck protocols; 1.5 mm used for superficial line treatment (décolletage, surface wrinkles). Brow lift protocol uses 4.5 mm transducer at brow/forehead zones.\n\n**Gateway posture:** Exact transducer selection, energy levels, line density, and pass counts per indication are in Merz Aesthetics clinical training materials and IFU. The range approach: "SMAS-level + deep dermis combination for structural protocols; add upper dermis pass for surface improvement." [Ultherapy IFU →]\n\n## Pre-Treatment Protocol\n\n- Topical anesthetic (EMLA or compound) 45–60 minutes pre-treatment\n- Oral analgesic (ibuprofen, acetaminophen) 30–60 minutes pre-treatment — standard practice given procedural intensity\n- For high-energy protocols: optional nerve block consideration (mental nerve, supraorbital nerve) for patient comfort\n- Document any recent filler (wait minimum 2–4 weeks if filler in planned treatment zone)\n\n## Treatment Delivery\n\n- Ultrasound gel applied; coupling verified via imaging window before energy delivery\n- Use imaging feature to confirm tissue depth — particularly important around TMJ, parotid, marginal mandibular nerve zones\n- Mark treatment vectors for brow lift: energy lines directed obliquely superiorly at forehead level\n- Pass density: higher density = more TCPs = more aggressive response. Standard protocols define lines per zone.\n- Stay ≥1.5 cm from known nerve pathways (marginal mandibular branch at mandibular border)\n\n## Post-Treatment Protocol\n\n- Immediate icing for comfort\n- NSAIDs as needed for post-procedural discomfort (typically 24–72 hours)\n- No specific wound care — no surface disruption\n- SPF and sun avoidance recommended\n- No restrictions on retinoids, exfoliants, or topicals post-treatment\n- Reassess at 90 days for results assessment and retreatment planning',
  '0b47b7aa-fbd6-4ec4-9dae-c0e5b869536f',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'b8c9d0e1-f2a3-4567-bcde-567890012307',
  'da25d447-c316-40b2-802e-e190c0bdbd9f',
  '1c9acf3e-8753-4bd3-af98-9372c994eec3',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'Ultherapy PRIME — Patient Education',
  E'## What Ultherapy Does\n\nUltherapy PRIME is the only non-invasive device cleared by the FDA to lift the brow. It uses focused ultrasound energy to reach and stimulate the same layer of tissue that surgeons lift during a facelift — without any surgery, needles, or incisions. The result is genuine structural lifting that addresses the root cause of facial sagging.\n\nHere''s what makes it different: most non-invasive skin treatments work at or near the skin surface. Ultherapy''s energy travels through the surface without affecting it and targets a depth of 4.5 mm — where the SMAS layer sits. The SMAS is the tissue sheet that gives your face structural support. When it loosens with age, the overlying fat pads and skin sag. Ultherapy creates a controlled repair response in this layer, stimulating collagen synthesis and tissue tightening at the structural level over the following 2–3 months.\n\n## What It Addresses\n\n- **Brow ptosis (drooping brow):** The only non-invasive FDA-cleared brow lift treatment\n- **Jawline and lower facial laxity:** Jowling, softened definition\n- **Neck laxity and "turkey neck":** FDA-cleared for neck and under-chin improvement\n- **Décolletage lines and wrinkles:** FDA-cleared for chest treatment\n- **Submental fullness component from laxity:** Tissue tightening under the chin\n\n## Why Ultherapy, Specifically\n\nThe SMAS-level energy delivery is what distinguishes Ultherapy from most non-invasive devices. Other skin tightening treatments work at the dermis — Ultherapy goes deeper to the structural layer. This is why it produces measurable lifting — not just skin quality improvement, but visible upward movement of ptotic tissue.\n\nThe built-in ultrasound imaging lets your provider see the tissue layers during treatment, confirming the energy is going to exactly the right depth. This isn''t just technical — it means your treatment is being delivered with verified precision.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**Comfort level:** Ultherapy is more intense than many non-invasive treatments. Numbing cream and pain medication beforehand significantly improve the experience. Most patients describe it as noticeable warmth and intermittent intensity. The treatment takes 60–90 minutes depending on areas treated.\n\n**Afterward:** Some redness, mild swelling, and tenderness for 24–72 hours. A small number of patients have brief numbness or tingling that resolves within weeks. No surface disruption means you can return to normal activities same day.\n\n**Results:** Collagen remodeling takes time. Noticeable improvement typically appears at 4–6 weeks; the full result is appreciated at 90 days. The lifting effect continues to build for 2–3 months post-treatment.\n\n**Maintenance:** Clinical results last 12–18 months in most patients. Annual maintenance treatment sustains the lifting effect.\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nUltherapy is for patients who have genuinely sagging tissue and want the closest non-surgical result to a lift. If your concern is "everything is heading south and topical products aren''t keeping up," Ultherapy addresses the structural mechanics — not just the surface appearance.\n\nThe FDA brow lift clearance is meaningful: this is the clinical evidence threshold, not a marketing claim.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nUltherapy lifts structure; it does not add volume or address dynamic lines. Most patients benefit from:\n- Ultherapy for structural lifting and laxity\n- Dermal filler to restore volume in areas that lifting reveals as hollow\n- Neurotoxin for dynamic expression lines\n\nSequencing: energy treatment (Ultherapy) before filler placement in the same zones.',
  'dff4a45b-8832-4063-a5a2-4064ce8e346f',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'c9d0e1f2-a3b4-5678-cdef-678901234408',
  'da25d447-c316-40b2-802e-e190c0bdbd9f',
  '1c9acf3e-8753-4bd3-af98-9372c994eec3',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'Ultherapy PRIME — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"Is this the same as Thermage?"**\nDifferent technology, different mechanism, different depth. Thermage uses monopolar radiofrequency energy targeting deeper dermis. Ultherapy uses focused ultrasound reaching the SMAS layer — deeper than Thermage. For brow ptosis and significant structural laxity, Ultherapy''s deeper reach gives it a differentiated lifting effect. Both are legitimate skin tightening options; the right choice depends on your anatomy and concerns.\n\n**"How painful is it?"**\nUltherapy is more intense than many non-invasive treatments — this is because the energy reaches a deeper layer than surface treatments. Your provider will use numbing cream and may recommend oral pain medication beforehand. With adequate preparation, most patients complete the treatment comfortably. Setting the expectation upfront prevents surprises.\n\n**"Can I get a facelift effect without surgery?"**\nUltherapy provides measurable lifting — FDA-cleared for brow lift — but the magnitude of lifting is less than surgical correction. For mild to moderate laxity, Ultherapy produces clinically meaningful lifting results. For severe laxity, surgical consultation is appropriate to set realistic expectations. Ultherapy is an excellent option for patients who are not candidates for or interested in surgery.\n\n**"When will I see results?"**\nYou may notice some immediate tightening due to TCP contraction. The primary result develops over 60–90 days as collagen remodels. Most patients report their best result around the 90-day mark.\n\n**"How long does it last?"**\nClinical results typically last 12–18 months. Annual retreatment is the standard maintenance protocol — treating once a year sustains the lifting effect as natural aging continues.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"I''m worried it will hurt too much."**\nUltherapy has evolved significantly in comfort — the PRIME version and current protocols with pre-medication make the experience very manageable for the vast majority of patients. The intensity of the treatment reflects the depth of energy delivery, which is precisely what produces the structural result. Your provider can describe exactly what to expect for your specific protocol.\n\n**"Can''t I just get surgery?"**\nFor patients with mild to moderate laxity, Ultherapy delays the need for surgery and preserves surgical candidacy for a later time. Many patients who have Ultherapy at 45 find they still achieve excellent results at 55 because they maintained their structural foundation. It''s not surgery vs. Ultherapy — it''s Ultherapy now, surgery later if ever needed.',
  'dff4a45b-8832-4063-a5a2-4064ce8e346f',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'd0e1f2a3-b4c5-6789-defa-789012345509',
  'da25d447-c316-40b2-802e-e190c0bdbd9f',
  '1c9acf3e-8753-4bd3-af98-9372c994eec3',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'Ultherapy PRIME — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\n**SMAS-level energy delivery:** The defining differentiator. No other non-invasive device consistently reaches and treats the SMAS layer. This is the tissue surgeons lift — Ultherapy''s ability to reach it non-invasively is the basis of its FDA brow lift clearance and its structural lifting claims.\n\n**FDA brow lift clearance (unique):** No other non-invasive device has this clearance. It is a hard clinical differentiation point that providers can articulate without hedging.\n\n**Real-time visualization:** MFU-V — the V stands for visualization. The imaging confirmation of tissue layers during treatment is an accuracy and safety feature differentiating Ultherapy from non-imaging ultrasound devices.\n\n**PRIME platform:** Merz''s 2023–2024 PRIME system includes new transducers with improved energy delivery efficiency and comfort improvements over earlier Ultherapy systems. PRIME is relevant when comparing against older Ultherapy installations at competing practices.\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\nTransducer physics: focused ultrasound at 4/7/10 MHz frequencies creates TCPs (thermal coagulation points) at precisely defined depths via piezoelectric focusing. Each TCP is approximately 1 mm³. Standard full-face protocol delivers 600–900 TCPs in a session. At 4.5 mm depth, TCPs reach SMAS fascia and platysma — the heating triggers collagen denaturation + Type I/III collagen synthesis response that contractures the SMAS tissue. Simultaneously, dermal transducers (3 mm, 1.5 mm) treat the dermal collagen matrix for surface line improvement. [peer-reviewed: Alam M. Dermatol Surg 2010; Kenkel JM. Aesthet Surg J 2014]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\nFDA clearance data: 73.1% brow elevation responders at 90 days (510k clinical trial). Alam et al. Dermatologic Surgery 2010 (industry landmark study): statistically significant improvement in neck/submental laxity. Kenkel et al. Aesthetic Surgery Journal 2014: prospective multicenter study on lower face/neck. Literature base for Ultherapy is among the strongest in non-invasive energy devices, including multiple RCTs and controlled prospective studies. Evidence level: Level I–II.\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Feature | Ultherapy PRIME | Sofwave | Morpheus8 |\n|---------|----------------|---------|----------|\n| Maximum depth | 4.5 mm (SMAS) | 1.5 mm (mid-dermis) | 8 mm (body fat) |\n| FDA brow lift | YES (unique) | No | No |\n| Structural lifting | High | Mild | Low |\n| PIH risk | None | None | Low |\n| Visualization | Yes (MFU-V) | No | No |\n| Evidence level | Level I–II | Level II | Level II |',
  'ca5b121f-878f-4256-a461-0d0b57d6f255',
  'draft', 1
);

-- ============================================================
-- LUTRONIC HOLLYWOOD SPECTRA
-- Product ID: be46f975-99d7-4772-867e-744814626654
-- Category: Pigment & Skin Rejuvenation (b35c36c4-ee76-422d-89a6-0e7a4af568b9)
-- Technology: Q-switched Nd:YAG 1064nm / 532nm, nano & picosecond pulse modes
-- FDA-cleared: pigmented lesion treatment, tattoo removal, skin resurfacing
-- Key protocol: Hollywood Laser Peel (carbon peel)
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'e1f2a3b4-c5d6-7890-efab-890123456610',
  'be46f975-99d7-4772-867e-744814626654',
  'b35c36c4-ee76-422d-89a6-0e7a4af568b9',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'Hollywood Spectra — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nHollywood Spectra (Lutronic) is a Q-switched Nd:YAG laser system operating at 1064 nm and 532 nm wavelengths. The system delivers nanosecond-duration pulses in Q-switched mode for pigment and tattoo removal, and millisecond-duration pulses in long-pulse mode for vascular and toning applications. A proprietary "Hollywood" protocol (carbon peel) uses topical carbon paste and low-fluence 1064 nm laser to resurface and tone the skin. FDA-cleared for the treatment of benign pigmented lesions and tattoo removal. [Lutronic 510k K133029]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\n**Q-switched 1064 nm:** Selective photothermolysis targeting melanin (in endogenous pigment lesions) or tattoo ink particles (in exogenous pigment). Photomechanical disruption (not thermal) of melanin-containing cells and ink particles, which are then phagocytosed and cleared. Very short pulse duration (nanoseconds) minimizes thermal spread to surrounding tissue. [peer-reviewed: Goldberg DJ. Lasers Surg Med 2008]\n\n**Q-switched 532 nm:** Higher absorption by melanin and hemoglobin; more superficial penetration. Used for epidermal pigmentation and vascular lesions with high melanin content.\n\n**Hollywood Laser Peel (carbon peel) — low-fluence 1064 nm with carbon paste:**\n- Topical carbon paste applied to face\n- First pass: carbon on skin surface — photomechanical exfoliation of carbon particles + desquamation of dead skin cells\n- Second pass: lower fluence — mild photothermal stimulation of dermis for collagen stimulus\nNet result: skin brightening, pore minimization, mild resurfacing without ablation. No downtime. [manufacturer protocol; peer-reviewed: Kim HJ. J Cosmet Laser Ther 2019]\n\n## FDA-Cleared Indications\n\n- **Benign pigmented lesion treatment** (lentigines, café-au-lait, seborrheic keratoses) [510k]\n- **Tattoo removal** (multi-color; 1064 nm for dark/blue/green; 532 nm for red/orange) [510k]\n- Skin resurfacing applications [510k]\n\n**Off-label field uses (gateway posture):** Melasma treatment (low-fluence toning protocol), generalized skin brightening/toning, sebaceous hyperplasia, acne vulgaris adjunct, onychomycosis. These are widely used off-label applications with varying evidence levels. [field practice; peer-reviewed]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Strong candidates:** Patients with solar lentigines, café-au-lait macules, unwanted tattoos, general skin dullness, enlarged pores (Hollywood Peel). \n\n**Fitzpatrick safety — CRITICAL (Safety Floor):**\n- Nd:YAG 1064 nm has the BEST Fitzpatrick safety profile of any laser for pigmentation treatment because 1064 nm has low melanin competition → lower epidermal damage risk\n- However, PIH REMAINS a risk at any wavelength in Fitzpatrick IV–VI with aggressive settings. Start conservatively with test spots, lower fluences, longer interval between sessions for darker skin types.\n- Melasma is a particularly PIH-risky indication in darker skin — QSYAG toning for melasma requires very low fluence and experience. Risk of worsening melasma with aggressive treatment is real. [peer-reviewed: Sarkar R. J Cutan Aesthet Surg 2012]\n- 532 nm has MORE epidermal melanin absorption → higher PIH risk in Fitzpatrick IV+ — use 532 nm cautiously in darker types\n[Lutronic IFU; peer-reviewed]\n\n**Contraindications (Safety Floor):**\n- Active skin infection or open wound in treatment zone\n- Photosensitizing medications (isotretinoin, doxycycline) — increase photosensitivity and adverse event risk\n- Known keloid history for ablative protocols\n- Pregnancy\n- Very recent tan (sun-darkened baseline melanin → increased burn risk) [Lutronic IFU]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Common:** Transient erythema, mild edema, transient darkening of pigmented lesions before clearance (characteristic "ash" response post-treatment), purpura in some vascular applications.\n\n**Uncommon:** Post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) — particularly in Fitzpatrick IV–VI or with aggressive parameters; textural changes.\n\n**Rare/serious:** Scarring (very rare with appropriate settings); hypopigmentation from over-treatment of melanocyte-rich zones; paradoxical tattoo darkening (iron oxide pigments in cosmetic tattoos — pre-test always). [peer-reviewed; Lutronic IFU]\n\n**Tattoo darkening warning:** Iron oxide pigments (white, flesh/pink cosmetic tattoos) can oxidize and darken after Q-switched laser. Test spot MANDATORY before treating cosmetic eyebrow tattoos or permanent makeup. [Lutronic IFU; peer-reviewed]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes\n\nBenign pigmented lesions: typically 1–3 sessions for complete clearance of solar lentigines; café-au-lait macules require more sessions. Tattoo removal: highly variable by ink color, depth, and age — typically 6–12+ sessions. Hollywood Peel: immediate skin brightening; series of 4–6 monthly sessions for sustained improvement. Evidence for melasma toning: mixed; some series show improvement, recurrence is common. [peer-reviewed: Goldberg DJ. Lasers Surg Med; Kim HJ. J Cosmet Laser Ther 2019]',
  'f34284d6-192b-4981-95ea-5cbbd612fa76',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'f2a3b4c5-d6e7-8901-fabc-901234567711',
  'be46f975-99d7-4772-867e-744814626654',
  'b35c36c4-ee76-422d-89a6-0e7a4af568b9',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'Hollywood Spectra — Technique Guide',
  E'## Wavelength and Mode Selection\n\n- **1064 nm Q-switched:** Dark ink tattoos, deep/brown pigmentation, melasma toning, Hollywood Peel. Safer for darker Fitzpatrick types.\n- **532 nm Q-switched:** Red/orange/yellow tattoo ink, superficial epidermal lentigines in lighter skin types. Higher PIH risk in Fitzpatrick IV+.\n- **Long-pulse mode:** Vascular applications, hair removal — distinguish from Q-switched mode in protocol planning.\n\n**Gateway posture:** Exact fluence (J/cm²), spot size, pulse duration, and pass number per indication are device-dependent and in Lutronic IFU and clinical training. Characterize as: "low-fluence for toning and darker skin types; higher fluence for lentigines in lighter skin; incremental progression per session." [Lutronic IFU →]\n\n## Hollywood Laser Peel Protocol Overview\n\n1. Cleanse face thoroughly; apply thin uniform layer of carbon paste\n2. Allow carbon to dry 5–10 minutes\n3. First pass: Treat at standard fluence — photomechanical "pop" of carbon particles; patients describe popping sensation\n4. Second pass: Lower fluence — photothermal dermal stimulus\n5. Post-treatment: cleanse, apply moisturizer and SPF\n6. Patient downtime: typically none to minimal (mild flushing)\n\n## Fitzpatrick Protocol Adjustments\n\n- **Fitzpatrick I–III:** Standard protocols; test spots still recommended for first session\n- **Fitzpatrick IV:** Reduce fluence 20–30% from baseline; longer intervals between sessions; post-treatment hydroquinone pre- and post-conditioning for melasma cases\n- **Fitzpatrick V–VI:** Very low fluence only; test spot in non-conspicuous area required before treating; 532 nm generally avoided; extended post-treatment observation; written consent for PIH risk\n\n## Post-Treatment Protocol\n\n- Strict sun avoidance x 4 weeks post-treatment for any pigment applications\n- Physical SPF 30+ daily\n- No exfoliants/retinoids x 5–7 days\n- For melasma/Fitzpatrick IV+: hydroquinone 4% or kojic acid pre- and post-treatment cycle\n- Tattoo removal: petrolatum dressing immediately post; healing per standard wound care x 5–7 days\n\n## Combination Sequencing\n\nQ-switched laser is generally compatible with neurotoxin (same or different session). Avoid laser near recent filler injection sites (minimum 2–4 weeks). For combined pigment + laxity treatment plans: laser first for pigmentation, then filler/energy devices for structure — or staged by zone.',
  'fb9e21b8-5a67-4acc-a8ab-36459fe4c07c',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'a3b4c5d6-e7f8-9012-abcd-012345678812',
  'be46f975-99d7-4772-867e-744814626654',
  'b35c36c4-ee76-422d-89a6-0e7a4af568b9',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'Hollywood Spectra — Patient Education',
  E'## What Hollywood Spectra Does\n\nHollywood Spectra is a laser treatment system that targets pigmentation — brown spots, sun damage, uneven tone, and unwanted tattoos — using focused light energy that selectively breaks up pigment without damaging the surrounding skin. It''s also the technology behind the signature "Hollywood Laser Peel," a no-downtime skin brightening treatment that celebrities famously choose before red carpet appearances.\n\n## What It Addresses\n\n**Pigmentation concerns:**\n- Brown spots and age spots (solar lentigines)\n- Sun damage and uneven skin tone\n- Melasma (using low-fluence toning protocol — with appropriate setting of expectations)\n- Skin dullness and textural unevenness\n\n**Tattoo removal:** Q-switched laser is the gold standard for tattoo removal. Multiple sessions over several months progressively clear the ink as the immune system removes the shattered particles.\n\n**Hollywood Laser Peel:** The zero-downtime brightening treatment. A thin layer of carbon paste is applied to the face, then the laser gently vaporizes it along with dead surface skin cells. The result is immediately brighter, smoother-looking skin — often preferred in the week before a big event. A series builds cumulative improvement.\n\n## Why Nd:YAG Specifically\n\nThe 1064 nm wavelength used by Hollywood Spectra has a particular advantage: it has lower absorption by surface melanin than shorter-wavelength lasers. This means it can treat pigmentation concerns with a significantly better safety profile for darker skin tones than many other laser systems. It is one of the few laser wavelengths well-documented for use in patients with deeper complexions.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**Pigmentation treatment:** A sensation of snapping heat during the session (short, tolerable). Spots often darken briefly before flaking off over 5–10 days — this is the normal response. Sun protection is essential post-treatment.\n\n**Hollywood Laser Peel:** Very minimal sensation during treatment; no real downtime. Skin appears brighter and refreshed within hours.\n\n**Tattoo removal:** Multiple sessions required (6–12+ depending on ink color, density, age). Each session, the tattoo fades incrementally. Full clearance of dark ink is achievable in most cases; colored inks vary.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nHollywood Spectra addresses pigmentation and skin quality. It does not address volume loss or skin laxity. A complete facial rejuvenation plan for a patient with both pigmentation and laxity concerns typically combines laser treatment for tone + structural treatments (filler, Ultherapy, Morpheus8) for architecture. Sequencing: pigmentation treatment and structural treatments can be done in the same plan, staged appropriately.',
  '2f0e0278-12f1-4836-8cf4-e0985d7d053f',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'b4c5d6e7-f8a9-0123-bcde-123456789913',
  'be46f975-99d7-4772-867e-744814626654',
  'b35c36c4-ee76-422d-89a6-0e7a4af568b9',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'Hollywood Spectra — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"How is this different from IPL?"**\nIPL (intense pulsed light) and Q-switched Nd:YAG work differently. IPL uses a broad range of light wavelengths; Nd:YAG uses a single specific wavelength. The Q-switched mechanism delivers extremely short, powerful pulses for photomechanical pigment destruction — which is the standard mechanism for tattoo removal and spot clearance. IPL is better for vascular redness and diffuse sun damage; Q-switched laser is superior for discrete pigmented spots and tattoo removal.\n\n**"Will my dark spots get worse before they get better?"**\nYes — this is the expected response. Pigmented spots typically darken immediately post-treatment (appearing as a darkened crust), then gradually flake away over 5–10 days revealing clearer skin underneath. This is not a complication; it''s the treatment working.\n\n**"How many sessions does tattoo removal take?"**\nIt depends significantly on the tattoo''s age, ink colors, depth, and your immune system. Black and dark blue ink responds best; lighter colors (yellow, white, pale green) are hardest to clear. Expect a minimum of 6 sessions, often more, spaced 6–8 weeks apart. Most tattoos can be cleared or significantly faded.\n\n**"Is it safe for my skin tone?"**\nThe 1064 nm wavelength used by Hollywood Spectra has a strong safety record for darker skin tones because of its lower surface melanin absorption compared to shorter-wavelength lasers. Your provider will adjust settings for your skin type and may do a test spot first to confirm your response.\n\n**"What is the Hollywood Laser Peel?"**\nA carbon-paste laser treatment that provides zero-downtime skin brightening, pore refinement, and surface smoothing. It''s a favorite pre-event treatment because the results are visible immediately and there''s no recovery required. A series of 4–6 treatments builds cumulative improvement.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"It takes too many sessions."**\nTattoo removal is a process of progressive clearance, not instant erasure — that''s the biology of how ink clears from tissue. The benefit is that each session is short and the interval between sessions (6–8 weeks) gives your immune system time to clear the shattered ink particles. Most patients see meaningful fading after 2–3 sessions and find the process worth it for permanent clearance.\n\n**"I''m worried about laser damaging my skin."**\nQ-switched laser is among the most-studied aesthetic laser technologies, with a decades-long safety record. The mechanism (photomechanical) is fundamentally different from ablative lasers that vaporize surface skin. Your provider will customize settings to your skin type to minimize any risk.',
  '2f0e0278-12f1-4836-8cf4-e0985d7d053f',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'c5d6e7f8-a9b0-1234-cdef-234567891014',
  'be46f975-99d7-4772-867e-744814626654',
  'b35c36c4-ee76-422d-89a6-0e7a4af568b9',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'Hollywood Spectra — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\n**Nd:YAG wavelength Fitzpatrick safety:** The 1064 nm wavelength is the dermatological standard for laser treatment in darker skin tones because it has the lowest epidermal melanin absorption of any laser wavelength in clinical aesthetic use. This translates to a lower PIH risk profile vs. 755 nm Alexandrite, 694 nm Ruby, or 532 nm KTP in Fitzpatrick IV–VI — a significant market differentiator when a practice serves diverse patient populations.\n\n**Hollywood Laser Peel protocol:** The carbon peel protocol is a differentiating no-downtime brightening treatment that drives repeat visits and is marketable by name. It provides a service tier (express skin brightening) below more intensive pigment treatments.\n\n**Dual wavelength (1064 + 532 nm):** Enables treatment of both dark pigmentation (1064 nm) and vascular/red ink (532 nm) from a single platform, broadening treatment indications.\n\n**Lutronic platform:** Hollywood Spectra is part of Lutronic''s platform with Genius (RF microneedling), Clarity II (diode laser), and Spectra (the base system). Practice economics benefit from multi-indication coverage.\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\n**Q-switched nanosecond mechanism:** A Q-switch shutter allows energy to accumulate in the optical cavity, then releases it in a very short (6–12 ns) high-peak-power pulse. Peak power in the megawatt range creates photomechanical effects (photoacoustic pressure wave) in target chromophores. This is the same mechanism used in all Q-switched lasers for tattoo removal. The Hollywood Spectra system operates at 1064 nm and 532 nm with configurable pulse duration modes including nanosecond and quasi-long-pulse. [Lutronic 510k; peer-reviewed: Goldberg DJ. Lasers Surg Med 2008]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\n**Q-switched Nd:YAG for pigmentation:** Multiple Level II studies demonstrate efficacy for solar lentigines, café-au-lait macules, and Nevus of Ota. Hollywood Spectra specifically has published evidence for the Hollywood Peel protocol (Kim HJ. J Cosmet Laser Ther 2019) showing skin brightening outcomes.\n\n**Tattoo removal:** Nd:YAG 1064 nm is the evidence-based standard for dark ink tattoo removal, with decades of published data.\n\n**Melasma:** Evidence is mixed. Some series show improvement with low-fluence toning; recurrence is very common (melasma is a systemic pigmentation disorder, not a localized pigment spot). Patient counseling on recurrence risk is essential. Evidence level: Level II-III for melasma, Level I–II for spot/tattoo indications.\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Feature | Hollywood Spectra (QS Nd:YAG) | IPL | Picosecond Laser |\n|---------|------------------------------|-----|------------------|\n| Mechanism | Photomechanical (Q-switched) | Photothermal | Photomechanical (picosecond) |\n| Tattoo removal | Standard | Not effective | Superior (faster) |\n| Fitzpatrick safety | High (1064 nm) | Moderate | High (1064 nm pico) |\n| Hollywood Peel | YES (signature protocol) | No | Some variants |\n| Capital cost | Moderate | Lower | Higher |\n\nGateway posture on picosecond: Picosecond lasers (e.g., PicoSure, PicoWay) produce faster tattoo clearance in some studies and may be more effective for certain tattoo colors. For practices without picosecond technology, Nd:YAG remains the clinical standard with extensive evidence.',
  'b55d7ec0-ffb8-48c6-8a88-ca404242e090',
  'draft', 1
);
